<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Characteristic Species</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Salvia</i> <i>mellifera</i> is dominant or co-dominant in the shrub canopy with <i>Adenostoma</i> <i>fasciculatum</i>, <i>Artemisia</i> <i>californica</i>, <i>Baccharis</i> <i>pilularis</i>, <i>Diplacus</i> <i>aurantiacus</i>, <i>Encelia</i> <i>californica</i>, <i>Eriogonum</i> <i>cinereum</i>, <i>Eriogonum</i> <i>fasciculatum</i>, <i>Hesperoyucca</i> <i>whipplei</i>, <i>Lotus</i> <i>scoparius</i>, <i>Malacothamnus</i> <i>fasciculatus</i>, <i>Malosma</i> <i>laurina</i>, <i>Opuntia</i> <i>littoralis</i>, <i>Rhus</i> <i>integrifolia</i> and <i>Salvia</i> <i>apiana</i>. Emergent trees may be present at low cover. </div>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Vegetation Layers</h4>
	<div class="text">  Shrubs < 2 m; canopy is continuous or intermittent. Herbaceous layer is variable; grasses and herbs are seasonal. </div>
</div>

        
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Membership Rules</h4>
	<ul class="text">
		
		<li><i>Salvia mellifera</i> > 60% relative cover in the shrub canopy (Borchert et al. 2004, Evens and San 2005).</li>
		
		<li><i>Salvia mellifera</i> usually > 60% or combined with a coastal shrub species > 30% relative cover in the shrub canopy (Klein and Evens 2005, Keeler-Wolf and Evens 2006).</li>
		
		<li><i>Salvia mellifera</i> > 50% relative cover, or > 30% relative cover when <i>Rhus integrifolia</i> or <i>Opuntia littoralis</i> is present (Rodriguez et al. 2019).</li>
		
	</ul>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Habitats</h4>
	<div class="text"> Dry slopes and alluvial fans. Soils are shallow.  </div>
</div>

        
