<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Salvia mellifera </i>is an open, shallow-rooted shrub that grows to 2 m in height. Twigs and leaves are glandular and highly aromatic. Plants produce numerous volatile compounds that may be important in herbivore or pathogen defense. They are drought tolerant by leaf curling rather than through leaf drop (Gill and Hanlon 1998) but are still considered to have a suite of drought-deciduous characteristics by Rundel (2007). Winter- and spring-blooming flowers are a rich source of nectar for native and introduced bees. Gravity and ants disperse seeds, which collect in the soil as a seed bank. Seeds often have low germination rates unless exposed to light or components of fire, but heat from fire may reduce germination rates (Keeley and Fotheringham 1998). Seedlings establish in clearings among older shrubs when soils are moist. Plants take two or more growing seasons to reach maturity. Plants sometimes sprout from the base. Recruitment is primarily by seed (Montalvo and McMillan 2002b). <br/>
<br/>
<i>Salvia mellifera </i>has the widest range of any of the <i>Salvia </i>shrubby sage species of the coastal sage scrub. In the northern portion of its range, stands usually appear on relatively xeric, well-drained exposures, whereas, in the south, stands tend to be on more mesic slopes with shallow soils. <i>S. mellifera </i>hybridizes with <i>S. apiana. </i>Where their ranges in southern California overlap, <i>S. mellifera </i>tends to occur in flatter and wetter microsites, while <i>S. apiana </i>occurs on drier slopes. Conversely, where <i>S. mellifera </i>overlaps in range with <i>S. leucophylla, </i>the latter tends to occupy more mesic sites. Hybrids between <i>S. mellifera </i>and <i>S. apiana </i>occur in recently disturbed areas and elsewhere in the coastal sage scrub (Kirkpatrick and Hutchinson 1977, Malanson 1984, Mooney 1977.) </div>
</div>

    
	
	
