<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Fire Characteristics</h4>
	<div class="text"><i>Salvia mellifera </i>sprouts moderately well after lowintensity fire, and stands are likely to survive and regenerate through root crown sprouting and through abundant seed germination. <i>S. mellifera </i>regenerates mostly from soil-stored seed after higher severity fire (Gordon and White 1994, Horton and Kraebel 1955, Keeley 1998b, McMurray 1990e). In addition, postburn reestablishment varies geographically. <i>S. mellifera </i>sprouts more often at lower elevation, maritime sites where coastal sage scrub species are more common as compared to higher elevation inland sites where chaparral species are more common (Westman 1991, Malanson and O’Leary 1982).</div>
	<table class="zebraStripe">
		
		<tr>
			<td class="key">Fire return interval</td>
			<td>Medium (15-90+ years)
				
			</td>
		</tr>
		
		<tr>
			<td class="key">Seasonality</td>
			<td>Late summer-fall
				
